INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '374a1c3f-a1f8-4580-9cc5-ee151a32432a',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$OpenAPI — Spec-First vs Code-First, Client Generation, and Docs That Actually Work$escape$,
  $escape$Spec-first means writing your `openapi.yaml` before any implementation. Your API contract is the source of truth — teams can generate server stubs, client SDKs, and mock servers before a single endpoint exists. Code-first generates the spec from annotations or reflection at runtime, which keeps the spec in sync automatically but couples your contract to implementation details.

For client generation, `openapi-generator` and `@hey-api/openapi-ts` consume your spec and emit typed SDKs. With `openapi-ts`, you get a fully typed `client.ts` with request/response types derived directly from your `components/schemas`. This eliminates hand-written API wrappers entirely.

For docs, Scalar and Swagger UI both consume the spec via a single URL — but Scalar renders `$ref` chains, `oneOf`/`anyOf`, and examples far more cleanly. Pair with `redocly lint` in CI to enforce naming conventions (`camelCase` operationIds, required `summary` fields) before the spec ever reaches consumers.

Spec-first wins when multiple teams consume the API. Code-first wins for solo projects where the spec is a byproduct, not a contract.$escape$,
  $escape$// @hey-api/openapi-ts — generate typed client from spec
// openapi-ts.config.ts
import { defineConfig } from '@hey-api/openapi-ts';

export default defineConfig({
  input: 'https://api.example.com/openapi.yaml',
  output: { path: 'src/client', format: 'prettier' },
  plugins: [
    '@hey-api/client-fetch',
    '@hey-api/typescript',
    '@hey-api/schemas',
  ],
});

// Usage — fully typed, no hand-written wrappers
import { getUserById } from '@/client';
const { data, error } = await getUserById({ path: { id: '123' } });$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
