INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '0fb6d6b1-8a46-4a3d-9dda-10fd4867a8dc',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$OpenAPI — URL vs Header Versioning and How to Document Both$escape$,
  $escape$OpenAPI 3.x has no native versioning construct — versioning is an API design choice you encode into your spec. URL versioning (`/v1/users`, `/v2/users`) is the most tooling-friendly approach: each version gets its own `servers` entry or a separate spec file. Header versioning (`Api-Version: 2024-01-01`) requires documenting a custom request header as a `parameter` at the path or global level with `in: header`.

For backward compatibility, use `deprecated: true` on individual operations or schemas rather than yanking them. Pair this with a `x-sunset` extension (Zalando convention) to signal removal dates. When evolving schemas, prefer additive changes — new optional properties don't break existing clients validated against the old spec. Use `allOf` to extend base schemas rather than mutating them.

For multi-version specs, `$ref` shared components from a common `components.yaml` and overlay version-specific deltas. The OpenAPI Overlay spec (v1.0 draft) formalizes this pattern — define a base spec and apply targeted `update` or `remove` actions per version without duplicating the entire document.$escape$,
  $escape$# openapi.yaml — header versioning + deprecation pattern
paths:
  /users:
    get:
      parameters:
        - name: Api-Version
          in: header
          required: true
          schema:
            type: string
            enum: ["2023-01-01", "2024-06-01"]
      responses:
        "200":
          description: OK

  /v1/users:
    get:
      deprecated: true
      x-sunset: "2025-12-31"
      summary: "[Deprecated] Use header versioning instead"
      responses:
        "200":
          description: OK$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
