INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '21fc8853-23c3-4272-a5c8-7eb4c64075d6',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$OpenAPI — Designing Filtering & Sorting Query Parameters the Right Way$escape$,
  $escape$OpenAPI 3.x lets you formally describe filtering and sorting conventions in your `paths` using `in: query` parameters, giving clients machine-readable contracts for what's filterable and how. Define each filter as its own named parameter (`status`, `created_after`, `tag`) rather than overloading a generic `filter` string — this enables validation, documentation generation, and SDK auto-completion. For sorting, the de facto convention is `sort=field:asc` or `sort=-field` (minus-prefix for descending), and you can enforce it via a `pattern` constraint in your schema. Combine this with `$ref` components so filter schemas are reusable across endpoints. For range filters, use paired params (`price_min` / `price_max`) and mark them as non-required with `nullable: false`. Always document defaults explicitly using `default:` in the parameter schema so generated clients don't silently omit them. Swagger UI and Redoc will render each param as a distinct input, making the API self-documenting without extra effort.$escape$,
  $escape$parameters:
  - name: status
    in: query
    schema:
      type: string
      enum: [active, archived, draft]
  - name: created_after
    in: query
    schema:
      type: string
      format: date-time
  - name: sort
    in: query
    schema:
      type: string
      pattern: '^-?(created_at|name|score)$'
      default: '-created_at'
  - name: limit
    in: query
    schema:
      type: integer
      minimum: 1
      maximum: 100
      default: 20$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
